column12: Description
@. Needed in CDCE prior to main DCE specification for syntactical purposes.
Begin a DCE separator string.
End a DCE separator string.
The DCE range character. Used to represent ranges in DCE. See the wiki for more information.
Used to denote the union of two records. See the wiki for more information.
Begin a DCE number.
End a DCE number.
Substitution character for an unknown value.
Internal DCE calendar identifier for the Gregorian calendar.
Positive value (syntactical representation — This is not the + character)
Negative (syntactical representation — This is not the − character)
Drop back to the core sheet (no meaning in EDF)
Drop back to the enclosing sheet (no meaning in EDF)
Begins a DCE region (no meaning in EDF)
Processing use only (not for interchange)
Sometimes used as a visible word separator, e.g. in Anoej
Special casing considerations for Turkish
Special casing considerations for Turkish

This denotes content that is not "bound" (given a context of a page, etc.) to be within — in other words it is what a plain text file is to a word processing file with page formatting — content with no context given for presenting it

Also used as a line separator by Microsoft Word and Powerpoint which use it to contrast with the character used as a paragraph separator (sources: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3380538/what-is-a-vertical-tab http://unicode.org/reports/tr13/tr13-9.html )
A variant of Dc120
Begin Base 64 encapsulated UTF-8
End Base 64 encapsulated UTF-8

This Dc is used for embedding arbitrary keyed ID/data pairs in a document. Standard structure: Followed by base64-encoded data identifying a fragment, then Dc 202 (End keyed embed ID sequence), then by the base64-encoded fragment itself, then by Dc 201 (End keyed embed fragment).
See description for 200
See description for 200
Arbitrary binary data (base64 encoded, no semantic significance assigned to it)
See description for 203
Used to replace an incoming character whose value is unknown or unrepresentable in Unicode
Used to replace an incoming character whose value is not mapped to a Dc (document component)
Beginning of a document
